</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1D2536900159A23DC8B7AA12FDB50FD8" blockId="1.[151,1437,1306,1727]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579">
Judging from the presence of males in samples from southern 
<collectingCountry id="658D76000159A23DCB4BAA12FC380C54" box="[875,943,1306,1331]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="579">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="790B4B610159A23DCBE1AA12FBC10C54" author="Mound" box="[961,1110,1306,1331]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" refString="Mound, L. A. (1976) The identity of the greenhouse thrips Heliothrips haemorrhoidalis (Bouche) (Thysanoptera) and the taxonomic significance of spanandric males. Bulletin of Entomological Research, 66, 179 - 180. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0007485300006593" type="journal article" year="1976">
Mound 
<number id="AB5224B70159A23DCC3DAA12FBC10C54" box="[1053,1110,1306,1331]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" value="1976.0">1976</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and southern 
<collectingCountry id="658D76000159A23DCD25AA13FAAE0C55" box="[1285,1337,1307,1330]" name="Peru" pageId="1" pageNumber="579">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="790B4B610159A23DCD69AA12FEDC0C30" author="Mound" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R. (1996) The Thrips of Central and South America: An Introduction. Memoirs on Entomology, International, 6, 1 - 488." type="journal article" year="1996">
Mound &amp;Marullo 
<number id="AB5224B70159A23DC92FAA36FEDC0C30" box="[271,331,1342,1367]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), this species presumably originated in the southwestern part of the Amazon basin. However, it is now found worldwide, and breeds on the leaves of many plant species in a wide range of families. Living mainly on older leaves, particularly of plants that are growing sub-optimally (
<bibRefCitation id="790B4B610159A23DCBCDAA8EFB1E0CF8" author="Mound" box="[1005,1161,1414,1439]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" refString="Mound, L. A. (1997) Biological diversity. Chapter 6. In: Lewis, T. (Ed.), Thrips as Crop Pests. CAB International, Wallingford, pp. 197 - 215." type="book chapter" year="1997">
Mound 
<number id="AB5224B70159A23DCC6EAA8FFB1E0CF8" box="[1102,1161,1415,1439]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), it avoids plants with trichomes on the leaves (
<bibRefCitation id="790B4B610159A23DC998AAA3FCA60CA4" author="Scott-Brown" box="[440,817,1450,1475]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" refString="Scott-Brown, A. S. &amp; Simmonds, M. S. J. (2006) Leaf morphology of hosts and nonhosts of the thrips Heliothrips haemorrhoidalis (Bouche). Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society, 152, 109 - 130. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1095 - 8339.2006.00560. x" type="journal article" year="2006">
Scott-Brown &amp; Simmonds 
<number id="AB5224B70159A23DCAD4AAA2FCA60CA4" box="[756,817,1450,1475]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The body colour varies with the degree of maturity, newly emerged females commonly have a yellow abdomen contrasting with the dark brown head and thorax, but the body of mature adults is dark brown, contrasting with the yellow legs. Males are smaller than females, with legs all pale and pore plates on sternites III–VII similar in shape and size to males of 
<taxonomicName id="DA9A4D130159A23DCC76A91EFB080F48" box="[1110,1183,1558,1583]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Heliothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis id="2FEEEA820159A23DCC76A91EFB080F48" box="[1110,1183,1558,1583]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="579">similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The 
<typeStatus id="C22188320159A23DCCC6A91EFADB0F48" box="[1254,1356,1558,1583]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579">lectotype</typeStatus>
of the subspecies 
<emphasis id="2FEEEA820159A23DC935A934FEE80F34" box="[277,383,1596,1619]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="579">angustior</emphasis>
, collected at “Paramaribo, 
<collectingCountry id="658D76000159A23DCA8FA932FC840F34" box="[687,787,1594,1619]" name="Suriname" pageId="1" pageNumber="579">Surinam</collectingCountry>
”, was studied at the Senckenberg Museum, Frankfurt, and has the metascutal triangle prolonged onto the metascutellum. This 
<typeStatus id="C22188320159A23DCBACA956FC640F10" box="[908,1011,1630,1655]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579">lectotype</typeStatus>
is accepted as the reference specimen for the name of this widespread pest thrips. Full nomenclatural details of the many synonyms of 
<taxonomicName id="DA9A4D130159A23DCCC2A98AFA0B0FFC" box="[1250,1436,1666,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Heliothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haemorrhoidalis">
<emphasis id="2FEEEA820159A23DCCC2A98AFA0B0FFC" box="[1250,1436,1666,1691]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="579">haemorrhoidalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are available in ThripsWiki (
<number id="AB5224B70159A23DC9F8A9AEFD820FD8" box="[472,533,1702,1727]" pageId="1" pageNumber="579" value="2015.0">2015</number>
).
</paragraph>
